1) POLICY RULES

- The expert clicks the cell directly below the current agent position, if it is empty, to allow the agent to fall down (seen in ~5/5 demos).
- The expert clicks a cell diagonally below and to the right of the agent, if the cell below is blocked and the diagonal cell is empty, to allow the agent to move diagonally down-right (seen in ~2/5 demos).
- The expert clicks a cell diagonally below and to the left of the agent, if the cell below is blocked and the diagonal cell is empty, to allow the agent to move diagonally down-left (seen in ~2/5 demos).
- The expert clicks a cell horizontally adjacent to the agent (left or right), if the cell below is blocked and the horizontal cell is empty, to allow the agent to move horizontally (seen in ~1/5 demos).
- The expert clicks a cell in the same column as the agent, below the agent, repeatedly, to clear a vertical path for the agent to fall (seen in ~3/5 demos).
- The expert clicks a cell in the same row as the agent, to the left or right, if the agent is at the edge and needs to move horizontally (seen in ~1/5 demos).
- The expert clicks the LEFT_ARROW cell when the agent is in the same row and to the right of the arrow, to move the agent left (seen in ~3/5 demos).
- The expert clicks the RIGHT_ARROW cell when the agent is in the same row and to the left of the arrow, to move the agent right (seen in ~2/5 demos).
- The expert clicks a cell to clear a path for the agent, but only if there is a STAR above the cell in the same column (seen in ~4/5 demos).
- The expert never clicks a cell if there is already a barrier (“#”) between the agent and the target cell in the same column (seen in ~5/5 demos).
- The expert clicks repeatedly on the same cell to ensure a path is clear, even if it appears already empty (seen in ~4/5 demos).
- The expert only clicks on cells that are empty (“.”), never on barriers (“#”), stars (“*”), or the agent itself (“A”) (seen in ~5/5 demos).
- The expert clicks on a cell if it is the first empty cell encountered when moving down from a STAR in the same column (seen in ~3/5 demos).

2) COUNTERFACTUAL DISTRACTORS

- Empty cells to the left or right of the agent, when there is no need for horizontal movement, are not clicked.
- Empty cells above the agent are not clicked, even if they are directly above or diagonally above.
- Empty cells that are not in the direct path (vertical or diagonal) between the agent and the STAR are not clicked.
- Empty cells that are blocked by a barrier (“#”) between the agent and the cell are not clicked.
- Empty cells in rows far below the agent, with no direct vertical or diagonal path, are not clicked.

3) GAME DYNAMICS

- When an empty cell below the agent is clicked, the agent falls down to that cell in the next state.
- If the cell below the agent is a barrier (“#”), the agent does not move vertically unless a diagonal or horizontal path is cleared.
- Clicking a cell repeatedly can convert it from empty (“.”) to a barrier (“#”), and then to a double barrier (“##”), and so on, forming a solid platform.
- The agent can move horizontally or diagonally if the corresponding cell is empty and the path is not blocked by a barrier.
- Clicking a LEFT_ARROW (“<”) or RIGHT_ARROW (“>”) cell moves the agent horizontally in that direction, provided the agent is in the same row and adjacent or within range.
- The STAR (“*”) remains stationary and does not move or change when cells are clicked.
- Barriers (“#”) are static and do not move unless the cell is clicked to change its state.
- The agent cannot move through barriers (“#”) or stars (“*”); only empty cells (“.”) are traversable.
- The agent’s position is always updated to the new cell after a valid move, and the previous cell becomes empty (“.”).
- The bottom two rows are always filled with barriers (“#”), except for the arrow cells.

